library(wordcloud)
## Loading required package: RColorBrewer
library(Rcpp)

Load report and conference call as a text files

mda <- read_file("MDA.txt")
press_release <- read_file("press_release.txt.")

Tokenize the text

tokens <- tibble(mda)
tokens <- tokens %>% tidytext::unnest_tokens(output=word, input=mda, token='words', to_lower=TRUE)
tokens <- tokens %>% mutate(order = row_number())

Remove stop words

# Load custom stopwords
custom_stop_words <- read_csv("stop_words_list.csv", col_names = FALSE)
## Rows: 1087 Columns: 1
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (1): X1
## 
##  Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
# Remove stop words
tokens <- tokens %>% 
  anti_join(custom_stop_words, by = c('word'='X1'))

Stemming and Lemmatizing

stemmed <- tokens %>% mutate(stem = SnowballC::wordStem(word))

Key words

set.seed(77)

stemmed %>% 
  group_by(word) %>% 
  summarize(count = n()) %>% 
  with(wordcloud(words=word, freq=count, min.freq=1, max.words=100, random.order=F, rot.per=0.30, colors=brewer.pal(8, "Dark2")))

Sentiment total

# load finance sentiment list and explore it
lm_dict <- tidytext::get_sentiments('loughran')

# view dictionary
lm_dict %>% group_by(sentiment) %>% summarize(count = n())
# Add sentiment
sentimented <- stemmed %>% 
  inner_join(lm_dict, by = 'word')

# Explore totals
sentimented %>% 
  group_by(sentiment) %>% 
  summarize(count = n(), percent = count/nrow(sentimented))
sentimented %>% 
  group_by(sentiment) %>% 
  summarize(count = n(), percent = count/nrow(sentimented)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x='', y=percent, fill=sentiment)) +
  geom_bar(width=1, stat='identity')

Sentiment total

lm_dict <- tidytext::get_sentiments('loughran')

lm_dict %>% group_by(sentiment) %>% summarize(count = n())
sentimented <- stemmed %>% 
  inner_join(lm_dict, by = 'word')

sentimented %>% 
  group_by(sentiment) %>% 
  summarize(count = n(), percent = count/nrow(sentimented))
sentimented %>% 
  group_by(sentiment) %>%

The MDA has much more negative or uncertain language roughly appears to be 90%. The press release is over 75% positive. This is to be expected, the MDA is about informing investors about all possible risks and considerations. It will use very legal and clinical language to clearly convey the information, and since its talking about risk the terms will lean negative. The press release is about controlling consumer sentiment and so regardless of the actual results of the company will be filled with positive and strong language. As an example the first line states the companys revenue is actually down slightly on one measure but the very next line emphasizes a pleased and revenue records in specific divisions rather than focusing on the down.
